data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10 (EF Core 10), the Cosmos DB provider allowed sync-over-async via an opt-in flag. **In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is removed entirely.** Every synchronous LINQ operator — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw an `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no workaround.

### The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);   // Add() is in-memory, stays sync
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

| Sync (broken in .NET 11) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

- `Add()` remains synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory.
- All callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` (this ripples up to controllers, etc.).
- The underlying reason: the Cosmos DB SDK is async-only, so sync wrappers were always blocking a thread pool thread. EF Core has now fully removed that path.
